,Recommended,236150,31886540,Posted: 21 May,all,Cookynator,"I'll just start off by saying I love this game. For all its faults and flaws, it is undoubtably a hell of a lot of fun. It's an open world, with so much going on that you're never short of anything to do. The story is decent, if nothing spectacular, but in getting away from that and forging a career for your captain, that's where the best of this game lies. You can do so much, from being a miner, to a pirate to playing Dora the space explorer to a mercenary. Hell, you can be all of those at once. I've clocked up a full day of play time on this game and feel I've only scratched the surface of what it has to offer.Pros:- Open world with many options to do things- Good leveling, balance and progression (most of the time)- Easy to use controls- SO MUCH TO DO!!!!- Decent graphics and a good selection of ships that both look and play in different styles- Easy to make money and progress, without it ever being too easy or too grind-y- Did I mention there's a lot you can do in this game?- The difficulty curve is well sorted and always gives you a sense of achivement without ever making anything too hardCons- UI can be a bit of a faff and it's easy to miss important things in combat until it's too late- Tutorial leaves a lot out and you have to figure quite a bit out as you go along (Not a problem so much as a downside to the large amount of content and devs clearly trying to avoid a bloated and OTT tutorial, just be aware you have to use your brain and think outside the box and read through the controls and manual sometimes)- Not a great game if you want something on rails that will hold your hand- Sometimes you spend 5 to 10 minutes sitting around as your ship flies from point to point- Occasionally has an air that it could have been even better than it isIn short a very good space sim that was everything I've always wanted a space sim to be. It manages to balance a good deal of content against lots of options without ever being bloated. It draws together all the core stuff you'd expect in a space sim into a very good package, and it keeps me coming back for more!8/10"
,Recommended,236150,32837226,Posted: 26 June,all,The Friendly Necromorph,"A truly fun game. SPG2 takes a lot of the best aspects of space simulators and combines that with high-paced, massive-ship combat, as well as a handful of RPG elements. There are skills and perks (that you gain by leveling primarily) that make you a better killing machine, and ships to compliment every style of play. You can be a trader just trying to make an honest buck, or you can take to piracy and capture and sell (or pilot) victim ships. There's also a reputation system among the factions, and there's a faction to support every style of play as well.The game certainly has its downsides. Loading in new areas is a little clunky, with the game occasionally stuttering, and the backdrop very suddenly changing, but these can be easily overlooked and foreshadowed by the great gameplay. Other than that, there are few downsides I can actually spot. Like some RPGs, enemies do scale with the area they're in. While their level will match yours (plus or minus a few levels), the NPCs in tougher areas will fly tougher ships, and this can sometimes hinder progress in the main storyline.Much like games of the same type, there is a good deal of down time where you're not really doing a whole lot, or you're just travelling. However, the game manages to strike a nice balance in that you'll often spend as much, or even more, time actually taking on missions or chasing bounties.Overally, while I certainly have my gripes about the game, that isn't a long enough list for me to not love this game, and the pros heavily outweigh the cons in every department. And, for those of you who may see this as a pro, you don't need to have played the first game to understand the story of this one. However, they did port the first game into this one as a free DLC."
,Recommended,236150,13134815,"Posted: 28 November, 2014",all,FattyMcFatfat02,"Loved this game. Felt like Privateer 2 without the cutscenes and sadly missing Clive Owen with Christopher Walkins :-( Freelancer should've been more like this. SG2 is a lot more open world than Freelancer which has its advantages and disadvantages. Personally, I found it purely an advantage. Unlike Privateer 2 and Freelancer you can truly just be a merchant if you want and switch effortlessly to being a badass kill everything murder ship at any space station/planet. Sometimes it's just the little things that make you happy... The graphics are great, the music not annoying, the abundance/ease of quickly accepting missions is a serious plus, and most importantly the flexibility of the game to allow someone the ability to play  the game how they want w/out the need of trainers, cheat codes, or cheat engine.Just like in the real world there are easy ways to make a quick buck with minimal returns or riskier methods that garnish heavy monetary rewards. I love that this game isn't afraid to make the playing field drastically uneven when it comes to rewards. Harder, almost always (there are times you get lucky/learn to exploit advantageous situations), means greater rewards! Learning the in game market is very beneficial. But it gets better, should you disagree w/me all you have to do is download any of the many mods and change how the game mechanics work. This game is a literal win-win. Small minor bonus pluses that I think are worth mentioning are; 1.) Achievements actually give you in game bonuses 2.) Blueprints that give better stuff that can't be bought 3.) Bounty hunting ( this is a mixed bag. this system could better implemented but I'll be damned if i didn't end up hunting everyone down!) 4.) Buying of certificates/licenses (w/game money and not real money) that give-in game bonuses for no other reason but to make the game fun (personally, I think it could have been better implemented but I sure as♥♥♥♥♥♥was excited to find a new one!). 5.) A good array of ships to pick from (potentially unlimited if you count mods... Just saying...) 6.) Personally, I found the system upgrade gimmick confusing at 1st but once understood, it opens the door to a lot of options that becomes unlimited if you include modding (just saying...).No game is perfect and this one isn't either. This is the disadvantage section of SG2. SG2 has some pretty poor optimization problems. 4-5 years ago my PC was a champ so it's aged a bit meow. Still, w/the level of graphics/visuals/objects it should run better. Especially since the video/graphics adjustment is bugged/non-functional. It's only a moderate complaint because the game allows mods and several are designed to reduce the toll taken on your PC. The rest of the comaplaints are mild at best because all are easily adjusted w/mods or are drastically overshadowed by the game's massive, bulging, make you scream in your pillow as you take it awesomeness so here goes- 1.) The voicovers are almost all a joke. They're done w/the stalest emotion possible. 2.) The story is kinda flat. Open ended games are prone to this a lot so it obviousley shouldn't be a huge unseen problem here. The game brings up interesting things here and there so kudos for the Devs for trying but it is still kinda... ummm... blah most of the time (kudos for the DEVs for doing such a good job to make the game so fun I really didn't care!)In short, my complaints are minimal at best and I had countless hours of fun playing it. I found it quick and easy to learn and SG2 left a lot of options for me to explore for future play throughs. I can't ask a game to do more than that but w/mods this game could be literally different everytime I played. I got it on sale and felt like I stole something. I would have happily paid full price and been more than content. This game is awesome, WOOF!"
