76561198034826075,Not Recommended,236150,34363841,Posted: 19 August,all,rwe19,"At $35 this game is way overpriced.  I can't recommend it at that price.  However, if you can get it on sale for $10 or less, then it's worth a play.PROS:Has some of the Freelancer spirit.Large variety of ships to own.Quick missions keep the pace fast.Good variety of things to do.CONS:Difficult interface that is NOT intuitive.  (However, go to the steam forums and watch the linked youtube videos.  Very helpful!)Main storyline is a convoluted mess.  Nothing to pull you in or make you care.  I was doing the missions just to do them--there was never any desire to see what happens next.  I still don't understand anything that was going on in it.MIssion difficulty level is meaningless.  If you take an assassination mission at your level you are just as likely to come up against three ""Impossible"" or ""Deadly"" ships as you are to find one ""Trivial"" enemy.Random crashes to desk top.  Make sure you hit a space station after every kill to save.Random deaths when not under attack.The only way to really make money is to capture ships.  The only way to capture ships is to own a large ship that can hold lots of troops.  I started with a gunship that couldn't capture anything, so it was a long grind until I could afford a larger ship and start capturing.The main storyline has cut-scenes that do not pause the game but hold your ship in place and prevent you from moving.  This is bad when you are under attack, and you are forced to watch helplessly as your ship is destroyed while listening to dreadful voice acting.There's really no way to communicate with your wing men, except to mark a target.  You can't give them any orders, and you aren't notified if they die in combat.  There were lots of times when I had no idea they had died until I happened to notice that I could hire another in a space port.Your targeting system shows no info on your targets unless you are facing them on the screen.  If they go off screen (imagine that in a spaceflight sim!) you have no idea of their status, distance, etc.There is a blueprint drop system that has you finding pieces of blueprints that can be assembled into rare system upgrades when you find all the pieces.  At least that's the theory.  The drop rate is so rare that you will likely never find all the pieces of any one blueprint.After ships are destroyed you can pick up the cargo they drop.  However, you have no way to tell what it is, and can find yourself picking up illegal goods literally seconds before you are randomly scanned by a patrolling ship and being ordered to drop the cargo you had no idea was illegal before you picked it up.  And losing rep over it.Overall the game does a decent job of bringing back fond memories of Freelancer, but has way too many irritating issues to make the experience worthwhile.  Definitely wait for a major sale before trying this one."
