76561198031041139,Recommended,236150,32197448,Posted: 5 June,all,Cyrus.Vance,"This is a Freelancer-type arcade space simulator with ship-to-ship combat, trading, mining, exploration etc.The game has its flaws, it comes from a small developer, but it is FUN.Lets start with the negatives:- the game has a steep learning curve, and the in-game tutorials are not the best, but if you have played similar games, you will be right at home.- controls are a bit weird too at first, but not that hard to learn, also you can remap the keys.- the reputation system is a bit simplistic, basically lawful-vs-evil, but it works. You can play as a ruthless pirate too :) Some factions will be hostile to you, regardless of your actions (because of story constrains).- heavier ships are almost always better, there is no point in flying smaller craft later on- the story is nothing to write home about, the voice acting is pretty amateur, sometimes nonexistent- the graphics is dated, but it is to be expected, the game is 3 years oldBut don't let these things discourage you, there is plenty of good here:+ space is pretty and has a good variety with dust clouds, asteroid belts, space stations, anomalies and so on+ there is a large variety of ships and ship classes+ there are many weapons, modules, mods, so you can customize and tweak your ship to your play-style or the current mission+ you can hire NPC mercenaries to help you out in tougher situations+ you can capture enemy ships and sell them for lots of money or keep them for your personal use, or just collect them in the hangar, like I did :)  Also because off this, pretty much every ship you see out there can be yours for the gold or the iron price :)+ you can only save at stations, so you take a risk every time you venture out into space+ beside the main mission line there are secondary missions for the big factions and random mercenary work+ the DLC missions add a couple extra hours of gameplay and new ships (especially the Titan, which is a beast as the name suggests)In conclusion: It's not perfect, but if it is on sale, and you like Freelancer-type games, go for it."
76561198093203804,Recommended,236150,13810223,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,probe,"Ok this is my edited review. I'll try and be semi-objective as I have interacted with the dev's, their moderator and the community for some time. But please read on and judge for yourself.Spg2 is a tactical space combat sim. I joined in EA and didn't play it for long due to hardware limitations on my account but liked the idea of a big massive universe where the player doesn't end up being the ""King of the Hill"" but just a small piece of a bigger universe. And Spg2 filled that need for me.This is not the most epic game I've ever played and I didn't expect it to be. But from a small ~10-ish Croation developer team I've been surprised. Not only have these guys made their own engine which shows beatiful graphical capability but they also constantly updated the game for almost a year after release with steady patching and a nice and cheap DLC while being constantly (I can't express how crazy these dev's are when it comes to listen to player feedback and troubleshooting with the community, it's unheard of) active on forums and responding to any bug report they received and fixing it with each new update. This is more than half the reason I'd buy any game they'd ever release.Well about the game; There are more in-depth Space Games out there, more epic stories to be told. But this game doesn't pretend to be any of that. It knows it's limitations as a huge space universe where the player is just a small piece of the puzzle. And it does that extremely well. Imagine being in a single-player MMO ( yeah kind of contradictory) but that's how this game treats you. You're nothing more special than the next dude around. You won't change the Universe all by yourself but you're just a small part in a bigger scheme. I love that sense of relating to your own existence in the world.How many games dares that anymore? In an age where we all feel we're the turning point and center of the Universe this game is a fresh breath teaching us the Universe doesn't resolve around us but we're just here to try to survive and do the best we can.There's no classic story arch to this game. You don't end up feeling like you're the king of the world. You're just a captain in the void trying to fend for him or herself. That's it. And from a philosophical perspective I love that notion. Too many games rub your need for being the ""one and only"". Not this game. This is reality expressed through a game. You're not gonna matter more than others but still need to claim your place in the world. That's beautiful and invigorating and  ... well poetic in some sense.There's a story (campaign) in the game that lends itself to the lore created in Spg1. But former knowledge of that is not required. I am still on the last mission of that storyline but that's not the reason I play Spg2. I don't relate that much to the story as such but enjoy the stories I can make with my own captains more.The game lets you choose between story and freeroam missions at a whim. You can always wander off to do randomly generated missions even when playing the campaign (campaign has a fixed character while freeroam lets you generate your own male/female character) and explore as you see fit. My preference and love for space was to be more of a ""freelancer"" doing randomly generated missions for different factions making friends and enemies along the way depending on my choice of the missions I'd carry out for different factions (help one faction=lose reputation with another faction and vice versa).The game can be a grind for some, other cherish that type of neverending possibilities and in Spg2 the ever-changing possibilities for changing your reputation and the constant randomly generated missions can keep you playing this for hours on end.Some days I just log in, cloak my ship and enjoy the scenery. Other days I just log in to take my temper out on whatever faction I'm currently in bad standing with and make them suffer.For a better description of the game check some videos on Youtube or other reviews. I'm still sold on this thing and the constant updates, a very nice and cheap DLC plus the upcoming FREE DLC makes me wanna recommend this game to everybody. Best and coolest development team I've ever meet and a hell of a positive and friendly community.This game is Steam History for the books. The reason I still get into EA from time to time is because of these guys right here.This is a game made by gamers to gamers. And a hella lot of respect for their interaction, back-and-forth, constant updates and pleasent attitude.If you're in doubt visit the forum. These guys are the future of gaming and a pinnacle of how developers can make gamers trust and cherish them again (yeah plenty of jaded gamers out there seeing bigger companies♥♥♥♥♥♥all over their customers or make highly dubious decisions).Edit: It should be noted that this game twists a few familiar concepts of games and how to progress the best possible way. There's not much ""hand-holding"" here but the forum is pretty active to anyone needing a tip or two on how to get the most of it and learn those ""different"" mechanics/understanding from what other games usually bring. So remember to pitch in with questions if there are any or you don't understand something. The early game in particular can be a bit rough for new players but once they get a hang of it it's really not that hard to understand.over 9000 / 10"
