,Recommended,236150,9986652,"Posted: 1 May, 2014",all,Boss weapons!,"Starpoint Gemini 2 is a game I've been following for a long time, hoping for a game that would dethrone Freelancer from its rightfull place. So far things look good and this might even be the case in the future, but as of now there's still plenty of work to be done. That doesn't mean SG2 wouldn't feel good to play. Does it?The game features a rather large open area The Gemini Star System. It's filled with stations, shipyards, bases, asteroid fields, junkyards, enemy ships, friendly ships, planets, anomalities, practically everything you would expect from a sandbox-type space game. It feels like there's a lot to do out there but at least for me that's not the case. This is because the game features very few different types of missions for the moment. There are freelance missions which you'll accept over the map view and then start them by docking with the correct facility, ship or planet. These missions usually involve hauling passangers or goods from the dock point to another. There are also scanning, repairing, patrolling and I think I even saw an assassination mission. These might keep you busy for a while but the samey repeating content of each mission type quickly lose their charm.The game's main emphasis is on space combat which for the most parts feels good. Ships fly in space and trade fire with missiles, beam weapons, plasma and railguns. Fighters fly out from the bigger ships and engage the enemies and boarding parties can devastate the enemy ships from within. You can fire manually or tell the game to target and fire on the target for you. I find this helpful since handling the ship in combat can be a real pain.You control your ship through two different control mechanics. The default one uses WASD to steer the ship while the mouse is used to target, shoot and activate buttons on the GUI. The second method is using the mouse to steer the ship. The ship turns along your mouse movement much the same way the default steering in Freelancer was handled. I prefer the former method in this game since using the mouse flight feels overly sensitive and I can't seem to make the ship fly straight or stay on target.In combat you also have to keep your ship from taking damage and face the stronger shield at your enemy while also focusing on distributing fire from your weapons evenly enough so you can have a sustained stream of fire at the target. I'm not sure if this is the intended way to fight but I've found it effective. You can also enter the turret view to move the camera and aim targets around your ship freely, this helps you to shoot targets your ships is not directly facing at.The combat is fairly entertaining, although like I mentioned above, steering the ship can be difficult and the default camera angle isn't helping much. When you need to fly on target it seems you have to place the target somewhere above your ship, close to the top edge of your screen. This is the actual direction the ship is moving towards to and it might take a while to get used to that. Also because of the odd camera angle I often had to keep the enemy ""above"" my ship to be able to fire the majority of my weapons at it. This just feels wrong, at least to me.The GUI is what really bothers me the most. It's overly colourfull, oddly clunky and the sound effects are horrendous. I have a tendency to go for a ""minimalist"" kind of look when it comes to user interfaces and such. In this game the UI makes me think of children toys, the large plastic kind with full of teeth marks and bright flashy colours. Actually, now that I think of it, the overall design and look of the game is overly shiny and gleamy. The ship designs could also be a tad more imaginative. Even the large battleships just look and feel like one-man fighter crafts even though they are supposed to be much larger than that.Overall the game has potential to be extremely entertaining. I like it so far even if the things I mentioned above might feel a little harsh. I've got great expectations for this game, although experience has taught me not to, but I can't help it. I'm longing for a good space combat/sim/whatever that has the feel and openness of Freelancer."
76561198006169257,Recommended,236150,8709820,"Posted: 14 January, 2014",all,E4GLEyE,"Only clocked in around 7 hours so far but woa... i am blown away.. even in alpha stage this game just shows an great potential and already nicely working elements such as capturing ships. You earn you money the way you want! nothing is forced as of now you can even flee or just ignore enemy ships... to be honest i think and hope that i found what i am looking for in a space game... but enough of me talking here is what i love and hate in it:Pro: Gorgeous graphics,Random Eventslots and lots of different ships to fight/flylarge map to explorecons: occasional frame drops (dusty asteroid field on the first spawn point... for me thats a brute videocard killer :D)Controls might be tricky (i use gunner view all the time while flying with keyboard its fine this way for me)alpha... i ignore the small bugs and stuff that are a usual visitor to ALL alpha stage games so ... yupoccasional small lock ups (1-2 sec) when an event/area is loading (but i kinda think this is only for me and my rather                        weak pc)Buy: If you want a very good space Single Player RPG and if you have the patience and nerves for an alpha (meself i did not encounter any huge bug and only had game crash one times so far)Dont Buy: if you are afraid of Alpha's (there is nothing wrong with that its totally acceptable) and if you are inpatient for them.9/10 for me (-1 is due to some lag issues I encounter)"
