76561197965285141,Recommended,236150,12156660,"Posted: 19 September, 2014",all,Frizzank,"First off I want to say I am really enjoying the game.  Unlike some space games, most things are strait forward, and I don’t feel the need for a spreadsheet full of stats just to progress in the game.  SPG2 does this rather well without feeling like its dumbing anything down.  It really feels like a modern take on Freelancer, which I thought was a fun game as well.The progression through the different levels is strait forward, but at the same time your profession choice seems to be inconsequential.  I wish you were given the profession choice after your first level up, so you could see what play style you actually preferred before making the permeate commitment.The camera movement is a bit wonky with no real free look option.  Instead you have a sluggish turret cam that you can manually aim your guns with. Ironically I rarely use to aim since my guns work much better on auto-fire, so I just use it to look around.The fire arcs for the guns are a neat gameplay mechanic but their representation in 3d space and on the 2d stats are hard to visualize. Often I think I should be hitting an enemy when I turn my camera to find out they are actually below me and outside my firing range since I don’t have a gun down there.There is a wide variety of ships and weapons in the game, but you are left up to your own exploring to find out what they are and where they are sold. This seems a bit odd to me since the market place has a great mechanic to show you what, and where the best prices for trade commodities are, but none for ships and weapons?The universe is large and has a good feel to it without feeling like your traveling through light-years of nothingness.  Every once and a while during PTE (Power -To-Engines) an enemy ship will drop out and take a shot at you or you will see an anomaly to scan and many other random events.  This adds a lot of fun and excitement to traveling that many games turn in to pain wrenching boredom just for the sake of realism.You have plenty of choice as to how you would like to play, pirate, enforcer, trader, miner or just the storyline.  The missions are varied and while there is the occasional grind it is rare and in no way feels necessary for progression.  Also with a large universe there is plenty of places to explore and room for several playthroughs without getting old.To sum it up I think it’s a great game that has a lot of replay potential.   So if you like the space game genre and would like a fun, non-hardcore game to jump in to, Starpont Gemini 2 is awesome choice."
