76561198007622141,Recommended,236150,12313534,"Posted: 1 October, 2014",all,fat4eyes,"A well-made space sandbox game, with great combat reminiscent of Star Trek Bridge Commander and a decent story campaign to see you off into the sandbox. It has a good dynamic side-mission generator, spawning mission locations near where you are so you don't spend too much time waiting when travelling from waypoint to waypoint. Though the game is set only in one star system (except for a short detour in the story campaign), the map is huge and is worth exploring just to see where you can get all the ships and weapons (of which there are plenty). There also seems to be a bounty system where you can find outlaws in powerful ships which can earn you lots of cash, though I haven't encountered any during my run through the campaign.Combat is similar to the old Star Trek Bridge Commander, where you have 4 sheild facings (and so does the enemy), and it becomes a matter of rotating through your sheilds to spread damage evenly, while trying to focus fire on only one of the enemy's shield face to get at his hull.You also earn experience which you can spend on 4 abilities to help you during combat. I played the engineer class, which focuses on buffs and debuffs and triggering these abilities do make a huge but not completely unbalancing effect on the results of combat. There are also enough choices in the skill progression that you can specialize your abilities, for example focusing one skill on reducing enemy weapon accuracy and another on dropping their shields.It does have some issues, The camera is a bit floaty and needs some time to get used to, the early grind can be really painful (I actually got too bored of the grind and just cheated the money), and the framerate can drop hard in the large ship battles in the story campaign. It also seems to have the ability to target enemy weapons and subsystems but I didn't see it make any difference during any of the fights. The UI flow also feels a bit rough in general, requiring too many clicks to do things, a rather unintuitive system for mounting weapons (instead of just having a drag and drop system), missing hotkeys (the 'mark target' action REALLY needs a hotkey, and the fighter launch hotkeys don't seem to work) among other things. Hopefully these will be polished as the game is updated.In the end though, the combat and the large and dynamic world makes it worth playing through the rough spots, and the campaign is interesting enough to lead you into the larger sandbox, which itself is worth exploring. Space sandbox games seem to finally be coming back into form, and this game is one of the good ones."
