76561198126959055,Not Recommended,236150,22301563,"Posted: 8 April, 2016",all,Joe Smilie,"It's not a bad game.I wouldn't pay the full price for this game. If you get it on sale, it's definately worth about 40 hrs of your time.--The space combat was very straightforward. Point and shoot. You win, you lose.Exploration was... very simple, almost entirely predictable.There were a lot of asteroid and debri fields. I don't think I spent more than 30min fumbling around in the very first one. I could have missed out on a very important part of the game by ignoring this activity.Trade was well thought out. Unfortunately there was no reason to participate in it. Overwhelming amounts of money had no real purpose. In other games, you could use massive fortunes to create space stations, buy sectors, buy planets, enable trade routes. I never saw that in this game (maybe I just missed it). Capturing and selling ships was more profitable, more entertaining.Money could be used to upgrade a particular weapon, endlessly, but it felt like a lazy money-sink. Investing in it made combat too easy. You could rent wing-men, but they were largely pointless if you acquired the above weapon.An alarming number of ships were useless in almost all situations. There didn't seem to be a way to improve a ship, if you liked it. There were modular upgrades that could be added and removed, but this seemed more like a standard approach - the upgrades must be done or this ship will be even more useless. I mention this, specifically, because I would have traded the money-sink weapon for a money-sink ship improvement system.The acting was good enough. The story was below average (which made the acting seem a lot worse than it was). Playing the main story may actually lower your over-all opinion of this game, which isn't uncommon for a space game. You have the option, in the game, to skip the main story entirely.There were some bugs in the game. Some of the bugs enabled exploits, so I'll avoid detailing them."
