,Not Recommended,236150,12251655,"Posted: 26 September, 2014",all,pixel all the things,"Lots of positive reviews on here convinced me to pick this one up while I wait for Star Citizen to drop. The comparisons to EVE are a joke and the two hold nearly nothing in common. Freelancer and Privateer? Sure. More recently, I'd compare this to Galaxy on Fire.SG2 is nothing more than a sandbox space game. If that's all you want then you'll get a decent game. The interface and user experience could use a bit of work as well as additional options to sort/organize commodities and equipment. I honestly didn't expect it to reach version 1 in it's current state and really it could have benefited from several more months of dev time. Customization is very limited. Combat is fairly solid. You're free to do as you please, exploring the galaxy and making friends/enemies wherever you go.I just wish there was something to drive the player beside their own goal. SG2 is lacking any sort of story. No big deal, it's a sandbox; I get it. Little story arc type missions would add so much though. Or a mission board to pick up missions in a more traditional fashion. Or the notion of of carrying out jobs for a particular company as a series of missions and work your way up. As it is, the game consists of flying around without direction, checking your map for freelance opportunities, accepting an opportunity, fly to the waypoint and either kill the badguy, or pick up and deliver cargo.  Mission done. Repeat until you can afford an ungodly expensive new ship and start again. They're the typical space game missions. It's a grind. And for me, if I'm going to grind at least give a me sense of purpose in doing so. Overall, this to me, is still a beta and was rushed out without any clear direction."
