,Not Recommended,236150,13669491,"Posted: 28 December, 2014",all,Llyagushen,"Seems unfinished. Tutorials are lacking.The combat is frustrating. For example, I had to search the wiki, guides and forums for some time to find the answer to a very simple question: how to attack neutral ships. The answer is - you have to attack them with manual fire, because automatic fire (aimed by AI) only works on targets that are already hostile. Which is another problem altogether: it's very hard to aim anything non-stationary with manual fire.There is no lead reticle, there is no auto-pilot which can help you align with the enemy so you can properly aim. I had to circle a neutral gunship for 10 minutes and was unable to hit it with light weapons, which don't require ammo (though I had a slow-firing, slow-recharging gun, might have been easier with a faster weapon). I had to use my heavy weapon after all, a homing missile, though I could finish my target with one or two shots from the light turret. I could accept the minimal UI assistance if I wasn't in command of a high-tech space ship. It's OK in WWII flight sim, and very much awful in a sci-fi setting.Maybe this isn't an issue when engaging big ships, but still is frustrating. There was a suggestion to add the lead reticule. It was suggested more than half a year ago, the developer said it's a good idea(http://steamcommunity.com/app/236150/discussions/3/540741131252960350/). Now the game is out of Early Access for more than 3 months and this is still not implemented.There are other things which still aren't working. For example, you can't delete completed missions from your quest log despite it having a ""Delete"" button. The only way to remove those completed quest is to load a savegame. It's not a big deal, but it shows that the game lacks polish. Another example: hitting ""Reset"" in keybinding menu will reset your graphic options along with the keys.I haven't played the campaign much. Still, it doesn't hook you very well. It starts as a generic revenge story. And without explaining anything the game wants you to go and collect stupid plot coupons to get any idea about what the hell is going on. In short: boring.The description on the store page says the game has ""tons of RPG depth"". I disagree. Having three classes each with just 4 skills, a dozen ""perks"" (rather dull compared to, say, Fallout perks) is not RPG depth in my book. And there isn't enough social interaction with NPCs for this game to feel like an RPG. Space Rangers 2 resembles an RPG much-much more than Starpoint Gemini 2 (it's also a much better game so try it if you haven't).The graphics are OK. Nothing impressive. I liked the music in the main menu. That's about all the pros I could find.All in all Starpoint Gemini 2 is a rather bland Elite/Privateer-like game without any cool features to be excited about. Or maybe I haven't found them yet. One reviewer mentioned the game being an acquired taste.I try it again after finishing with more worthwhile games I bought at the current sale, but right now it will have to rest. It's my first big miss during this sale."
