,Recommended,236150,25270314,"Posted: 31 August, 2016",all,Luke Groundwalker,Space Simulator: CheckAchievements: CheckStory: CheckFreeroam: CheckSingle-Player: CheckRPG: CheckDeveloper Responses: At the speed of lightNot developed by Hello Games: Check
,Not Recommended,236150,22240917,"Posted: 4 April, 2016",all,Bob Ross,"This Review is based on the ""Freeroam"" game and does not concern the storylinesStarpoint Gemini 2 (SP2) is a sort of tactical space-combat simulator with RPG elements. At the start of the game you pick a character avatar and name, a class and one of three starter ships. Then it plops you down in the newbie-friendly area of Planet Trinity and gets you started with some context-sensitive tutorials.Gameplay is fairly straightforward. You have a map of the universe, and as you fly around various missions become available. You can accept any of these missions; they can be a number of things: straight Assassination missions (destroy the target), Escort or protection missions (preserve an allied target and destroy enemy targets), repair missions (fly to a structure and use the middle-click context menu to repair it), taxi missions (fly VIP from point A to point B), smuggle missions (fly contraband cargo from point A to point B). Each mission provides some cash, experience and either positive or negative reputation.The reputation system is not spectacular. There are ""bad"" factions and ""good"" factions. Doing missions for the good factions, or blowing up the ships of bad factions, rewards positive rep. Vice-versa for the bad factions. If you want to work with the ""bad"" factions, you need to acquire negative rep. However, there are a handful of ""fanatic"" factions that you can never join, and destroying them ALSO rewards positive reputation,even if they are the target of a bad faction mission. I tried a couple playthroughs; the first time I didn't pay any attention to rep and within a few hours I was close to maxing out my positive rep (+2500 points). The next day I attempted to build negative rep, not knowing how the rep system worked (it's not explained well in the tutorials or anywhere else) and it took many hours of trial and error, and reading the Steam discussion forum, to figure out what was going on. In short the game is heavily balanced in favor of working for the ""good"" factions. The only way to change reputation outside of missions and combat is to find a ""good"" or ""bad"" structure and kill it (actually disable it, it's still there in a deactivated state) by holding down the fire button for a solid minute or two.Making cash in the game is equally frustrating. Most missions provide piddly amounts of cash, and the biggest incentive to earn money is to buy a bigger, badder ship. Missions also award experience, however, and raising your level tends to raise the level of threats you face. At level 10 there is a rather steep increase to the difficulty of missions involving combat. You are probably still in your gunship, when your targets become freighters and destroyers. This is even in the easiest area of the map (areas of the map are ""leveled"" in some aspect; how exactly is somewhat opaque). Effectively this locks you out of the most fun and rewarding missions, those involving combat. Inquiries to the devs on the Steam forums as to how this leveling-scaling works were ineffective.Ironically, the best way to make money is to simply pirate other ships. This is not inherently a ""bad"" move: as long as you are pirating the ships of the ""bad"" factions, you will gain positive reputation. Pirated ships call sell for between 100k to a million or more, depending on the ship and it's cargo. Capturing a ship is a fairly simple game of ""who has more troopers"". Even with extensive buffing of your troopers strength via skills and perks, it's effectively impossible to take a ship that has more men; taking one with equal numbers is a roll of the dice. There are videos available on the interwebs explaining this in more detail. Again, none of this is addressed in-game.There is more to talk about, such as the levelling, the exploration aspect, and the ""sideline"" missions that advance some sort of story in freeroam (it seems to be a ""good"" centric story, unfortunately for people hoping to be an enterprising space pirate; it is however completely optional). But I don't want to go on for ages. Is this game worth $42.00 (core game + DLC)? Absolutely not. It's a fairly amateur product that is struggling with balance and weird game-crashing bugs years after it's debut. The dev company is by their own admission very small, and their players seem to know the game better than them; unfortunately the wiki is highly underdeveloped, leaving brand-new players in the dark. This game was bought while it was on sale at 80% off; $10 is a perfectly reasonable price for a game that will entertain for about a week. If you're interested in deep simulation and RP opportunities, look elsewhere. If you want a pretty simple, fun game that looks good and doesn't take a lot of research to grasp, this may be the title for you."
76561197961498941,Not Recommended,236150,13260753,"Posted: 6 December, 2014",all,Fox,"Great concept, but falls well short of the X3 series.The storyline isn't bad, but the only decent way to make any speedy money is capturing ships.I love doing that, but Freelancer did a better job of letting you make money trading.I wouldn't have even written a review if it wasn't for the bugs.Ships that are 'trivial' ranked randomly had weapons that could one-shot your ship. I'm talking about a frigate that drops your cruiser or dreadnaught to 0 with a single beam blast or missile.  Break the Line had it happen time and time again. I only beat that mission by going back to a station each time I went to another waypoint to save.Towards (what I assume) is the end I was supposed to jump somewhere to take back the starpoint, only the game just went to a black screen.  I had become so increasingly buggy and the gameplay so slow at that point that I've decided to cut my losses and uninstall the game."
