,Not Recommended,236150,12306003,"Posted: 30 September, 2014",all,Segregator,"Thousands of backers and fans who were eager for this game to come out; several years of development to get it just so; and even early-access availability, supposedly to alpha and beta-test the game before its official release.  Yet still, the game is awful.I have only played a few hours of it, but I've managed to compile a small list of incredibly important things that you should know before deciding to purchase this game, in the order of importance:1.  Making in-game currency is slow, almost tedious about 90% of the time.  Granted, you can choose a number of ways in which to generate the income dependent on how you would like to play the game (mining, trading, bounty-hunting, completing freelance missions, etc), but ultimately the amount of money that you generate over time is a very slow crawl and makes purchasing better ships, weapon systems, and other important ship equipment almost not even worth the grind.2.  Because of the fact that you have to grind in order to make any money, you level up faster than you can improve on your equipment.  Upon checking the official forums, I discovered that this is apparently a known issue that they haven't had the chance to fix yet, so it might be patched up at a later time.  As a result of your leveling which outpaces your ship class and ship's equipment, you will continue to face increasing numbers, frequencies, and difficulties of enemies that you will have more and more trouble dealing with until you can finally purchase better equipment.  Of course, this basically means that you're almost always behind the curve no matter what as there is no way to slow down your leveling and everything gives you experience.3.  The statistics which indicate to you how difficult a challenge something is in the game are arbitrary.  For instance, the game will tell you the general threat level of red-outlined ships which are about to attack you, which should be an indication of whether you should stand your ground or turn and flee.  This ranges from ""Trivial"" to ""Impossible.""  I have been able to easily beat ""Impossible"" targets with ♥♥♥♥♥♥ ships and almost be totally destroyed by a ""Trivial"" ship in my brand new cruiser.  This same arbitrary system can be found in the instance of determining whether or not an enemy ship can be boarded and taken over by your troopers.  Generally, the lower the number of troopers on the enemy ship, the easier it'll be to overwhelm them.  This stops being the case after a few levels and, even with the maxed-out perk which increases your troopers' effectiveness by 15%, the smaller number of enemy troopers will steam-roll yours every time.Anyway, that's my two-cents.  On the plus side, the game is pretty and I liked where the setting was headed, but ultimately this is just a ♥♥♥♥♥ier version of EvE Online and not necessarily worth the price."
