,Not Recommended,236150,16553177,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,Swashblade,"After playing through the first few missions you'd be forgiven for thinking this was a pre-release indi title, with awful voice acting of poorly written dialogue giving it a horribly unpolished feel, and a tutorial given in the form of a series of short descriptions you need to click through for each UI element but lacking in any practical examples of how they're used leaving you bewildered as to how you're meant to control your ship.I got my first achievement purely by accident just by following the first waypoint . . . which turned out to be in the core of the planet I was trying to land on rather than, as I'd assumed, at some kind of space elevator docking station.  When I finally figured out how to land, visually it was much the same as crashing into it - I still flew to about the same range but instead of warning me to stop and then exploding, the ship stopped and I got the planet menu.While the game claims to support joystick control it's very much designed for mouse and keyboard, with the mouse leaving the targeting reticle wherever you last clicked something.  I ended up awkwardly using the joystick in my left hand and trying to target with the mouse before giving up in disgust and returning the controls to their default joystickless configuration.The starting spaceship flies like it's on rails regardless of the control method you choose and looking through the keybindings gives me no hope of more maneuverable craft later on - you can move forward, turn and roll.  No backward or lateral movement.  Your best bet in a firefight seems to be to leave the turrets on autofire and do your best to fly out of the way of your target's firing lanes.  High speed dodging just doesn't seem to be in the cards, contrary to what was shown in the trailer."
