,Not Recommended,236150,16336127,"Posted: 12 June, 2015",all,Hanabi,"I didn't enjoy the game. I played it till I got the controls down. But between a tutorial that dumps a bunch of dialog boxes on me. To a rather clunky space game control setting, I couldn't get myself enwraptured as much as I wanted to. I wanted something that would send me back to the days of Freelancer.For those of you who like space games, it has some real meat, but it is a different veriety of meat, much like the difference between Beef and Chicken.There was a lot of flying around doing nothing, the system travel gates required money and just dropped you into loading screens. And while the scale of the star system is right and the customizability is there. It lacked a certain charm. A polish.Plus!-Customizable Ships-Huge in depth system-Lots of ways to burn timeMinus!-Boring Non-Customizable Campaign Protagonist (I wonder why the same guy gets used game to game, is it the same guy?!)-Clunky combat controls-Flat uninvolving ports and planets. (At least early game)-The Tutorial---Notes to the Devs.I honestly respect the work you put on this game, and I can give you a few pointers.On a thread I read you spoke about how your hands on tutorial didn't please, and how other people complained about this tutorial. There is a middle ground, hear me out.Rather than dump it all at once in a click through while the game is paused, simply in the opening acts give a small, non intrusive note that tells you how to do something, without pausing, or forcing you to do it.For example when you start get a quick side note saying how to fly the ship. When you encounter your first enemy get a little side note without pause saying the right mouse button fires.What you have currently is page after page of tutorial sheets, which, while not as long as EVE is thrown far more upfront. Sure EVE had a lot more tutorial text, but EVE didn't dump it on you the first ten seconds.Secondly, the Protagonist. For a space RPG many people regard who's in the Cockpit as optional or make a character. In this case we have the typical inexperianced yet cocky caucasian male. But my question is, what if you made the protagonist for the actual game slightly more customizable. Give him titles instead of a direct name. Like his father saying 'son' while others call him by other things. Next, why not increase a few lines of dialog by adding gender options, a female voice actor and the ability to choose as many options as Freeroam? Really honestly give the illusion of choice to the player by letting them make the person they play as. Kind of like Bioware did with Shepard, Hawke or the Inquisitor. Sure you don't have to be that in depth about it with 3d renders. But a few portraits and the options would have been amazing.On combat, a good thing that most space games do, is have a lead indicator and a smoother method of control. In this case I felt like I was trying to reign in a finicky second hand robot. And the lack of a lead indicator made dogfighting a pain. (Not impossible, but annoying. I still won, but it wasn't as pleasent.)I think there really isn't much that can be done about the planets, except maybe adding a more visual docking procedure such as an orbital station or docking ring, or some sort of 'Decending/Ascending' animation. Secondly on the Travel Lines, instead of making it a loading screen jump pointer, make it a long thread that you can ride that steadily consumes money as you travel it, and you'll be booted from the stream when you run out or hit abort. Maybe add lane contols and make it work like a highway.---All and All I think this game does a lot right and a lot wrong, and I love the passion I see from the developers and can't wait to hear what Starpoint 3 might hold on the someday. If you come into this expecting the next Freelancer, you're probably not going to enjoy it. And the asking price for the features which are missing are pretty major."
