ung. And let's not forget the gems. Everyone likes to have their stinky pile of dung encrusted with the jewels of a king who painted a brilliant picture of even more elephant dung. Oh, but the setting is in space! How exciting! I'm sure I'd love to fly around in a massive piece of space dung as long as it looked pretty!The graphics are nice...but that is all.Worse voice acting than Darkstar One.There isn't a lot of customizability either. Ship classes and sizes range from petty-clunking-piece of space dung to giant piece of space dung, but with glasses so as to let you know it's the father of the bunch. Weapons come in a small amount of flavors. You have the shooty speedy laser lights known as railguns which you can barely see because apparently they shoot faster than light and do next to no damage. Next are the beam weapons which have their own subflavors of electricity, less electricity, and holy s*** there's so much electricity I can't even see what I'm shooting at. Which btw, I can't see an enemy ship unless I'm hugging their balls and by the time I can fire a missle at them, it might as well be shooting a fly with a watermelon, but don't fret because this watermelon will most definitly hit the fly because of guidance systems built into the watermelon itself.Explosions are also completely rediculous. If I'm fighting a large cruiser and I blow it up, I expect the explosion to fit the variant of the ship and it's systems. Instead, I'm treated to a super nova that kills my speakers (and ears), temporarily blinds me, and...the ship is still intact, allthough now instead of being called ""Super Mega Death Killer"" It is instead refered to by the game as ""Derelict"" Not Derelict Ship/Cruiser, just derelict. Oh but there's more! Indeed, if you shoot at the thing you were fighting just a minute ago, you'll spend another 10 minutes widdling away at its health bar until it finally explodes again. This time, you get access to the loot inside the ship and the model has completely vanished with no trace of debris. How boring...At any rate, I should have expected this from some random gaming group I never heard of nor seen any of their work because they don't offer demos. I'd ask for a refund, but I know how Lord Gaben is about the ""No Refund"" policy. So there you have it. A complete waste of time and money, though if you do buy the game and no life it enough, I'm sure one year later when you've completely forgotten about your friends and the fact that you even exsist, you'll have gained all the credits, mercenaries, and access to top of the line ships and equipment...which, as far as the leveling system goes for you and the enemy, will blow up in half a second due to the extreme damage output of whatever enemy you're fighting."
76561197960820471,Not Recommended,236150,12171683,"Posted: 21 September, 2014",all,Just,"Starpoint Gemini 2 is a sandbox spacegame.For now it is only about freelancing, while a story line will be added later on.You can earn your money from various random missions, mining, trading, fighting (loot) and capturing ships.The game has two huge issues:- the game mechanics- the balanceWhile the balance will most likely be adjusted later on, for now it is just wrong. And i am not talking about the strength balance but about balancing cargo size to item numbers etc. Sell values, ship size to speed and distance etc etc.Examples:When mining you need about 5 seconds to fill up your entire cargo hold. So you spent at least 95% of your time flying to the asteroid belt and back to the station to sell stuff, this makes mining insanly boring. The same goes for fighting and selling loot.After capturing a ship you need to fly it to a station, again, the capture process is a few seconds, the way to the station can be several minutes  depending on where you fought the ship.Every way of earning money feels like a boring grind.The game mechanics are a mess as well.Ships always have the same amount of turret mounts. Larger ships wont have larger weapons. So in the end, no matter how large your ship is, you will still use the exact same weapons you used on your starting ship. Additionally the larger ships are barely any stronger, they only have higher defensive stats.There is barely any feeling of progression during the game.All your weapons are turrets and each of them is only facing one side of the ship. So you got front rear and side turrets. Trying to manually fire them will result in only 1/4 of the turrets shooting. On close range projectiles wont hit, thanks to the point of view that makes it impossible to aim. On long range you wont hit anything as well, thanks to the relations between ship size, speed and weapon range. You can only manually aim at mid range.So after all the full fighting system is ""get into range, hit auto fire, wait for everything to be dead"".There is no depth in the fighting system at all. There is no chasing or trying to position yourself etc.While the map is huge, there is no point to ever explore it, as you get everything in the spawn system. Maybe later on the story line will force you to move around, but ""freelancing"" means you stay at the spawn station and barely move around.There is a skill system, that allows you to level and use skills during combat. As a figher you have 4 skills. After activating a skill it grants you a passive bonus to one weapon type for a certain amount of time. Obviously you will only level and use one skill. So the full skill system is only about hitting one button before combat and then wait until auto fire has killed everything.Once again this system has no depth at all.Finally:I know that the game is in early access and not finished, still the game mechanics, meaning the stuff that IS finished, is really bad and not working well. None of the game mechanics has any depth.After playing games like privateer, freelancer (and basically all other space games of the last 20 years) i cannot recommend buying this game, for now.However, the devs of SPG2 are interacting a lot with the community.So i hope that the game will improve a lot during the developement and i will update my review when this happens."
