,Not Recommended,236150,12303416,"Posted: 30 September, 2014",all,Eyh‼,"As a sandbox game, which many other people seem to enjoy, it has lots of possibilities. But, the campaign is very terrible and lackluster, and there's no good tutorial. The help system consists of screenshots and highlighted areas with captions and doesn't really teach you anything - it didn't even kick in until after I had managed to shoot a friendly planet a few times while trying to dock with it and launched again.Graphically, the ship models and stations look cool, but you don't really get to see details until you're practically nose to nose with them. The external holographic info boards outside stations make no sense to me. The angled third person chase cam makes it very hard to make your ship fly straight unless you're locked in to a waypoint. You also won't see anything happening on your ventral side because of the angles.The combat AI is terrible - as soon as your enemies get near you, they slow to a crawl, and so if you match speed with them, you're both crawling along. They'll do all sorts of flips to try to evade you while maintaining distance, which makes them ineffective at shooting you, while you chew away at their shields and hull for what seems like forever. Oh, and there's no projected flight marker on the hud either, so forget trying to use your primary weapons at range.The campaign doesn't do anything to teach you game mechanics either. It just consists of a few 'go here' waypoints, some dialogue, and kill/defend targets. Some of these waypoints are really far away, and take tens of minutes of doing nothing to get to. There are jump gates, but they're ridiculously expensive and you can't afford them doing the campaign alone. There's a few 'freelance' jobs along the way which are generally more kill targets, but they pay out very little. I also accidentally looted a contraband item, and couldn't figure out how to dump it. Oh, and there's no saving the game during campaign mode, you're at the mercy of their sporadic checkpoints, some of which occur before those long journeys doing nothing."
